
To start wsl on vscode:

1 wsl --install -d Ubuntu / wsl --install only
2 In VS Code → Press Ctrl + Shift + P → Type:
WSL: Connect to WSL

To create venv and use it:
1 python3 -m venv venv / python3 create venv venv
2 source venv/bin/activate
3 python3 -m pip install django
4 Verify installation:
python3 -m django --version

 To create django project:
 1 django-admin startproject <name of project>
 then To start app:
 1 python3 manage.py startapp <name of app>


sudo apt update
sudo apt install python3-pip -y
 if we get "No module named pip"


if recreate your virtual environment or venv faill
sudo apt update
sudo apt install python3.12-venv -y


pip freeze > requirements.txt  To collect installed tools

pip install -r requirements.txt To install tools on it

to install and use mysql:
1 sudo apt install mysql-server
2 sudo service mysql start
3 sudo service mysql status
4 mysql -u root -p
in deployment:
5 sudo mysql_secure_installation
This helps you:


And improve security.
Follow the prompts:

Set root password

Remove anonymous users

Disallow remote root login

Remove test database

Reload privileges

Then, create a separate MySQL user for your app instead of using root:

CREATE USER 'appuser'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'StrongPassword!';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON hertradebridge_db.* TO 'appuser'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;


That’s the production best practice.


